<task id="profile_dita_content">
  <title>How to Profile DITA Content</title>
  <prolog>
    <metadata>
      <keywords><indexterm>Profile DITA step by step<indexterm>conditional text<indexterm>profiling
              tutorial</indexterm></indexterm></indexterm></keywords>
    </metadata>
  </prolog>
  <taskbody>
    <context/>
    <steps>
      <step>
        <cmd><ph conkeyref="reusable.menus/Open-the-preferences-page"/>
          <?oxy_comment_start author="Mark" timestamp="20141009T153253-0400" comment="This is how to set it up. And it needs to say that it will be ignored if a subject scheme is in use."?>and
          go to <menucascade>
            <uicontrol>Editor</uicontrol>
            <uicontrol>Edit modes</uicontrol>
            <uicontrol>Author</uicontrol>
            <uicontrol>Profiling / Conditional Text</uicontrol>
          </menucascade> page and edit the <uicontrol>Profiling Attributes</uicontrol> table.
          <?oxy_comment_end?></cmd>
      </step>
      <step>
        <cmd>For DITA there are already default entries for <codeph>audience</codeph>,
            <codeph>platform</codeph>, <codeph>product</codeph>, <codeph>otherprops</codeph> and
            <codeph>rev</codeph>. You can customize the attributes and their values. </cmd>
        <info><?oxy_comment_start author="Mark" timestamp="20141009T153351-0400" comment="This is why it is a separate procedure. Setting up profiling attributes should be a separate topic that treats all the various methods."?>This
          is a one-time operation. Once you save the customized attributes and values, you can use
          them to profile any DITA project.<?oxy_comment_end?></info>
      </step>
      <step>
        <cmd>To use the profiling attributes set in the previous step, do one of the
          following:</cmd>
        <substeps>
          <substep>
            <?oxy_comment_start author="Mark" timestamp="20141009T153551-0400" comment="This is not a procedure, but a list of alternative. But the alternative have different scopes. a is for profiling topics. b is for profiling elements."?>
            <cmd>Right-click <uicontrol
                conref="../topics/oxygen-shortcuts-list.dita#oxygen-shortcuts-list/command_click"/>
              a topic reference in <uicontrol>DITA Maps Manager</uicontrol> and choose
                <uicontrol>Edit Profiling Attributes</uicontrol> from the contextual menu.</cmd>
          </substep>
          <substep>
            <cmd>In the <uicontrol>Author</uicontrol> editing mode, right-click <uicontrol
                conref="../topics/oxygen-shortcuts-list.dita#oxygen-shortcuts-list/command_click"/>
              an XML element and choose <uicontrol>Edit Profiling Attributes</uicontrol> from the
              contextual menu.</cmd>
          </substep>
          <substep>
            <cmd>Use the <uicontrol>Attributes</uicontrol> view to set profiling
              attributes.<?oxy_comment_end?></cmd>
          </substep>
        </substeps>
        <info>Turn on the <uicontrol>Show Profiling Attributes</uicontrol> option to display the
          profiling markup in the <uicontrol>Author</uicontrol> editing mode. </info>
      </step>
    </steps>
  </taskbody>
